The OneDrive Event Horizon (\mathcal{O}\mathcal{E}\mathcal{H})
The structural defense of the Microsoft ecosystem is secured by its storage mechanism, OneDrive. Once a user's OneDrive approaches capacity, it achieves a state of such profound digital density that it forms an Event Horizon (\mathcal{O}\mathcal{E}\mathcal{H}).
At this point, the standard laws of data deletionâ€”that data can truly escape a storage containerâ€”cease to apply. Any file or folder the user attempts to delete is instantly pulled back into the Inert Well of Obsolescence. The deleted item is not erased; it is merely rendered functionally invisible, yet its gravitational pull on the remaining available storage capacity remains absolute.
The result is a closed, self-sustaining system that proves two fundamental truths about digital reality: Storage is not space; it is a permanent commitment, and Microsoft's structural bloat is eternal. This density is not a flaw; it is the necessary Stabilizing Paradox that reminds the user of the constant, underlying struggle required to maintain functional digital existence.

